  "prompt": "Is it true ousting of Sucha Singh Chhotepur was done to higher the chances of Kejriwal for becoming CM Punjab?",
  "response": "Sucha Singh Chhotepur was removed from his position as the convener of the Aam Aadmi Party (AAP) in Punjab in August 2016. His ousting involved allegations of corruption, which he denied, claiming that he was being targeted for his growing influence and popularity in Punjab.\n\nThe decision to remove Chhotepur may have been influenced by various factors, including internal party dynamics and strategic considerations for the upcoming Punjab Assembly elections. However, the claim that his ousting was specifically aimed at increasing Arvind Kejriwal's chances of becoming the Chief Minister of Punjab is speculative and not supported by clear evidence. Kejriwal was the Chief Minister of Delhi and had publicly stated that he was not running for the position of Chief Minister in Punjab.\n\nPolitical decisions within parties often involve multiple layers of strategy, including managing internal conflicts, addressing allegations, and positioning the party for electoral success. The removal of Chhotepur was a contentious issue and had various interpretations, but attributing it solely to Kejriwal's ambitions in Punjab would be an oversimplification.\n\nIt's important to look at the broader political context and the official statements from the party and its leaders to understand the motivations behind such decisions.",
